\section{\underline{SUPPLEMENTARY INFORMATION}}

\section{Magnetometer principle}
The total spin of the atomic ensemble is defined as $\mathbf{J}=\left(  {J_x,J_y,J_z} \right)$. Here ${\mathbf{J}}$ is a quantum operator, and the components have the commutation relation $\left[J_y,J_z \right] = i J_x$. ${\mathbf{J}}$ is here defined as being unitless and equals the total angular momentum divided by the reduced Planck constant $\hbar$.
The equations of motion for the spin vector can be derived using the Heisenberg equation of motion

text:
\begin{equation}
\begin{pmatrix}
J'_y\\
J'_z
\end{pmatrix} 
=
\begin{pmatrix}
 \cos \Omega t & \sin \Omega t\\
-\sin \Omega t  & \cos \Omega t
\end{pmatrix}

\begin{pmatrix}
J_y\\
J_z
\end{pmatrix} .
\end{equation}
